The paper deals with models for lobbying in a probabilistic environment, which involves influencing voters' preferences of voting for or against multiple issues when the voters' preferences are represented in terms of probabilities. This falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT) as it involves strategic decision-making by multiple actors. The paper also proposes evaluation criteria and bribery methods, which can be seen as artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques. The analysis of the problems of lobbying in a stochastic environment involves computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and parameterized complexity (cs.DS). Finally, the paper provides approximability and inapproximability results, which can be seen as optimization problems in computer science (cs.SI).
